  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and conventions aimed at combating money laundering. Here's a breakdown of the key ones:\n\n*   **The United Nations Convention Against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (1988 Vienna Convention):** This convention was one of the earliest international efforts to address money laundering, primarily focusing on the proceeds of drug trafficking. It required signatory countries to criminalize the laundering of drug money.\n\n*   **The United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime (2000 Palermo Convention):** This convention expanded the scope of money laundering offenses beyond drug trafficking to include the proceeds of a wide range of serious crimes, such as organized crime, human trafficking, and corruption. It also emphasized international cooperation in investigating and prosecuting money laundering offenses.\n\n*   **The United Nations Convention against Corruption (2003 Merida Convention):** This convention focuses specifically on corruption-related money laundering. It requires states to criminalize the laundering of proceeds derived from corruption offenses and to take measures to prevent and combat corruption.\n\nIn addition to these UN conventions, the **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)**, an intergovernmental body, sets international standards for combating money laundering and terrorist financing. While not a treaty or law itself, the FATF's recommendations are widely adopted by countries around the world and serve as a benchmark for national anti-money laundering (AML) legislation. The FATF also monitors countries' compliance with its recommendations and identifies jurisdictions with weak AML regimes.\nThese are the main international laws addressing the issue, with FATF also taking a front seat due to the impact that their recommendations have in different countries.",
